The 2020-21 Student Artwork Calendar is complete! It is currently being printed and copies will be sent to each district family.

The printed calendars are scheduled to arrive at homes between September 24-26. For planning purposes, a PDF version of the calendar has been posted online in case you’d like to print out October to continue scheduling.

In addition, for the first time this school year, the District Family Handbook is a separate document posted online.

https://bit.ly/ESDcalendar

post_text: Have an interest in Computer Science and STEM? Then the 2020 Congressional App Challenge is for you! Open to all High School students, this national challenge invites groups up to four to create and submit their software application or mobile app on the platform of their choice. The winner will have the chance to attend the #HouseofCode Capitol Hill Reception in Washington D.C., and meet with Congresswoman Pramila Jayapal. Eligibility requirements and additional details here: https://bit.ly/2FAttyT

post_text: Feeling stressed out about the upcoming school year? Looking for strategies to help cope with the anxiety associated with being away from your friends? Starting September 9th, Meal kits with 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches will only be free to students who qualify for free meals. Reduced students will pay $2.00. Full pay students and non-students can purchase meal kit for $25.

Since we will need to enter student names in the computer at each transaction, we are trying to get ahead start on rosters. If you plan to pick up meals from one of our school sites please add your students name to a roster now by clicking on this link https://bit.ly/3gqfFnl . You only need to do this once and students will be on the roster until we return to in person instruction. Community locations will be firmed up by the end of this week and added to the survey.

To apply for Free or reduced meals please complete this application and turn it in at a meal site. English: https://bit.ly/ESDFoodApp For other languages visit: https://bit.ly/3aZ7v4y Hard copies of the application can be picked up and turned in at any meal site.

Please join us at our August EAACH meeting via Zoom! All students, family, staff, and community are invited to attend all EAACH meetings.

This month EAACH Leadership would like to invite everyone to have an equity-focused conversation on our hopes and fears for fall and Continuous Learning 2.0.

Date: Monday, August 24th, 2020 - Interpretation in Spanish Available
Time: 6:00-8:00 PM
Zoom link: https://bit.ly/2Yx9MP8

Please fill out the Student Intent Form 2020-21 for each student by Wednesday, Aug. 19. While all students will begin the school year in the fully remote learning model of Continuous Learning 2.0, the district needs to know which families will choose in-person learning, when it is safe to do so, and which families will continue with fully remote learning. The information is critical for planning purposes. Please login to your Skyward account to access the form. (This is different from the survey many families filled out earlier in the summer - this is a form and is required information for each student. Families will have an opportunity to change your intent as we get closer to the possibility of opening our buildings. Please give us your best answer that you have today.) Thank you!
https://bit.ly/StudentIntent

Congratulations to Courtney Wooten for being honored as an Emerging Leader 2020 in Snohomish County by The Herald!
As a district parent Courtney is an active member of our Equity Alliance for Achievement Committee (EAACH) serving as part of the leadership team and serves on her school Equity Team. She led the Black Lives Month of Action petition and has been doing consultancy work with our Diversity, Equity and Outreach department. Her invaluable contribution to her school, district and community as a whole should be celebrated. We are proud of her partnership and advocacy of district families!

A ‘mother interested in helping kids’ hopes to end stereotypes | HeraldNet.com https://bit.ly/2BQLFTB

All students who will continue with the Edmonds School District in the fall may keep their district-issued Chromebooks at home over the summer. We encourage all students to stay engaged in different learning opportunities.

All students who have graduated or will not continue with Edmonds School District in the fall are asked to return district-issued Chromebooks. Please contact the Student Tech Support team to schedule a time to drop off devices at the Educational Services Center. Student Tech Support may be reached at techsupport@edmonds15.org or 425-431-1211. Drop offs are by appointment only during summer hours, 8 a.m. to 4 p.m., Monday through Friday.

Join the Edmonds School District in honor of Juneteenth for a week
of education and action around Black freedom from slavery and the
ongoing Black struggle for freedom. Every day this week, a District leader will read a book at noon through the district's Facebook Live. Today, College and Career Readiness Specialist Ashley Kay Smith Speaks will be reading "I am Perfectly Designed". To see the full list of scheduled presenters and additional learning resources please visit our web page: https://bit.ly/2zyufKc

>>Please read the entire message by visiting our website: https://bit.ly/2UCcTDB<<

Dear Edmonds School District families,

As we plan for reopening our school buildings in the fall, we want you to know that the health and safety of our students, families, staff, and community members surrounding the COVID-19 pandemic comes first.

This morning, the Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction (OSPI) released state guidelines on how schools will reopen this fall. You can read the entire document on the OSPI website. The district is committed to exploring the viability of this reopening plan for in-person instruction.

We want you to know as Dr. Kristine McDuffy steps down from her position at the end of the month, she and our new superintendent, Dr. Gustavo Balderas, are working together with the district leadership to use the new state guidelines to help make specific plans for different school scenarios when we reopen in September.

>>Please read the entire message by visiting our website: https://bit.ly/2UCcTDB<<

post_text: The school board voted unanimously to change the last day of school to Friday, June 19, 2020. This new date coincides with the state's decision to not require the 2019-20 school year to go past June 19. The district’s last day of school was scheduled for Monday, June 22, 2020, which was pushed out due to snow make-up days.
text: The school board voted unanimously to change the last day of school to Friday, June 19, 2020. We want to let our families observing Ramadan know that our Grab and Go meal sites all have vegetarian and no pork meal options. These meals can be refrigerated for later consumption.
مع اقتراب حلول شهر رمضان ، نود ان نعلم عائلاتنا التي تحتفل بهذه المناسبة الدينية وشعائرها من صوم وصلاة، بأن كل المدارس التي تقوم بتوزيع الوجبات اليومية "Grab n Go" تقدم وجبات نباتية فقط و لا يوجد وجبات تحتوي على لحم الخنزير كما يمكنكم حفظ هذه الوجبات بالثلاجة و تناولها في وقت لاحق ما دام لم تفسد أو تسوء حالتها.
Ya que se acerca la celebración del Ramadán, queremos dejarle saber a nuestras familias que observarán el Ramadán que nuestro sitios de comidas "Grab n Go" tienen opciones vegetarianas y comida sin cerdo. Estas comidas pueden refrigerarse para su consumo posterior.

post_text:
During these unprecedented times the uncertainty that comes with COVID-19 and the impacts on our families significantly contribute to our stress and anxiety levels. While some stress can be a good thing as it motivates us to act, too much can become overwhelming and dysfunctional. It is important for us to attend to our mental health just as much as our physical health in order to promote healthy and adaptive coping skills.

Our district counselors and psychologists want to make sure families have the information and resources they need to support their student’s mental health. Staff are available for phone or Zoom collaboration so you may connect directly with school counselors or psychologists. Please visit our Mental Health Resources website for details:
bit.ly/ESDMentalHealth

post_text:
Edmonds School District has more than 18,000 Chromebooks in the hands of students in grades K-12. With all this technology out in the community, our wonderful team of technology experts are here to answer all your technology questions.

The Technology Department has expanded the hours of the Student Technology Support Team. The new hours are 8 a.m. to 7 p.m., Monday through Friday. If you need assistance with a Chromebook, login, or other student technology, please email techsupport@edmonds15.org or call 425-431-1211. In addition, if you haven’t had an opportunity to pick up your student’s Chromebook, reach out to Student Tech support to schedule a pickup at the Edmonds School District Office.

As of 12 p.m. Tuesday, March 10, 2020, we have no confirmed cases of COVID-19 among our students and staff. Snohomish Health District, which has local health jurisdiction over our community, continues to say that closing schools when there has not been a confirmed case in a student or staff member is not currently recommended. We will continue to take direction from the Snohomish Health District on possible school closures.

Although we are actively responding to this public health issue, we are still in the classroom where teaching and learning continue. Our staff is doing an incredible job remaining calm, staying positive and keeping up normal daily school routines as much as possible so our kids can feel safe and stay focused on learning.

Details: http://bit.ly/ESDCOVID-19

post_text: As of 12:30 p.m. Friday, March 6, 2020, we have no confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the Edmonds School District. The Snohomish Health District continues to recommend that schools without confirmed cases remain open. Beginning Monday, March 9, through Sunday, April 12: all sporting competitions, concerts, dances, plays and information nights are canceled or postponed. All local, out-of-state and international field trips are also canceled during that time. And, the district has suspended all community use during that time as well. The district will continue to track the situation and will update our community on our decisions past April 12. More details: http://bit.ly/ESDCOVID-19

Reminder: The rescheduled 2SLGBTQIA+ event is tomorrow, Feb. 12 from 4-9 pm at Meadowdale High School.

This community event is to support learning and provide resources to our 2SLGBTQIA+ students and families and continue to foster a community of allies in our district.
This event is FREE, you do not need to be there the whole time. Please attend the workshops that fit best.
At this event you will have the opportunity to learn:
1. Understanding gender diversity
2. Stories of families and students
3. Supporting your LGBT*Q+student’s emotional health and well being

*FREE Childcare and dinner will be provided. Childcare for children 3+ who are toilet trained

Please Register with this link: https://tinyurl.com/ESD2020

2. Stories of families and students

Edmonds School District students are producing the second annual TEDx event for local high school students! They are looking for student voices around the theme "Step One."

TEDx is a program of local, self-organized events that bring people together to share a TED-like experience. TED is a nonprofit devoted to spreading ideas, usually in the form of short, powerful talks.

There are many ways to get involved: apply to be a student speaker, nominate a potential speaker, volunteer, or simply attend the event. Learn more: http://bit.ly/2GYjyki

Save the Date!
May 30, 2020, 2:00 p.m. EDCC Black Box Theater

Swim lesson vouchers were sent home with each third grade student in the district. This free program for students is made possible by Verdant Health Commission in cooperation with the cities of Edmonds, Lynnwood and Mountlake Terrace.

Each third grade student receives three vouchers good for three sets of swim lessons that are redeemable at either the Lynnwood Pool, the Mountlake Terrace Pool, Yost (Edmonds) Pool or YMCA Dale Turner Pool. They are redeemable anytime in 2020. In addition, pool staff visit all third grade PE classes in the spring to provide water safety lessons.

More information about the program and vouchers can be found on the District Swim Lesson website: http://bit.ly/36WGmMk
text:
Swim lesson vouchers were sent home with each third grade student in the district. This free program for students is made possible by Verdant Health Commission in cooperation with the cities of Edmonds, Lynnwood and Mountlake Terrace.

Each third grade student receives three vouchers good for three sets of swim lessons that are redeemable at either the Lynnwood Pool, the Mountlake Terrace Pool, Yost (Edmonds) Pool or YMCA Dale Turner Pool. They are redeemable anytime in 2020. In addition, pool staff visit all third grade PE classes in the spring to provide water safety lessons.

More information about the program and vouchers can be found on the District Swim Lesson website: http://bit.ly/36WGmMk

post_text: Staff from our district are attending the annual Washington Educational Research Association (WERA)/Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction (OSPI) Assessment Conference today and tomorrow. A team from our district lead a presentation today on Culturally Responsive Data Collection. WERA is a non-profit dedicated to improving the practice of instruction, assessment, evaluation, conducting and applying educational research, and using data to inform instructional decisions.

post_text: 🍎Do you have a few hours to spare on Thursday morning?? Whether you are a parent, grandparent, community member (i.e. maybe you are retired or you have babies who will one day attend our district) -- PLEASE JOIN US for the Superintendent's Community Breakfast and School Tour! You will learn more about the Edmonds School District, the upcoming Bond/Levy and tour two different schools (College Place Middle and Madrona K-8. Did I mention you get to eat school breakfast too!? Oh, and you get to ride the school bus! Those who attended our tour a few weeks ago had such a great time! Some of them were retired teachers who worked in our district, they were so fun! We really encourage you to join us this Thursday morning! You will learn so much! Please RSVP and we hope you will attend!
